# GHML Sample Document

Welcome to **Generative HyperText Markup Language**. Every link below dispatches a prompt
to an LLM and generates its destination in real time.

---

## render — Full Page Generation

Clicking these links replaces the current view with a freshly generated document.
The generated document may itself contain `ghml:` links — this is the **recursive property**.

[Introduction to GHML](ghml:render "Write a friendly 3-paragraph introduction to Generative HyperText Markup Language — what it is, why it matters, and how it differs from traditional HTML. End with 3 ghml:render links to explore: the architecture, use cases, and security model.")

[Explore use cases](ghml:render "Generate a GHML document listing 6 compelling use cases for a document format where hyperlinks dispatch LLM prompts and generate destinations in real time. For each use case include a ghml:render link to generate a worked example." model=claude-opus-4-7)

[Deep dive: architecture](ghml:render "Explain the 5-layer GHML architecture: Parser, Context Builder, Prompt Router, Stream Renderer, History Engine. One section per layer. Each section ends with a ghml:action link to show a code sketch for that layer." context=page)

---

## nav — Navigation with History

Like `render`, but the browser back button works.

[Start a guided tour](ghml:nav "Generate the first page of a 3-part guided tour of GHML. End with a ghml:nav link labelled 'Next: Link Types →' that generates part 2." model=claude-opus-4-7)

---

## action — Inline Results

These stream output directly at the link's position — no navigation.

[Summarise this page](ghml:action "Write a 2-sentence summary of the document above." context=page inline)

[Generate 5 GHML link ideas](ghml:action "Suggest 5 creative ghml:render link prompts a developer might put in a product changelog document. Output as a numbered markdown list." inline)

[What is selected?](ghml:action "Describe what the user has selected. If nothing is selected, say so." context=selection inline)

---

## embed — Inline Widgets

Renders a self-contained widget at the link position.

[Show a comparison table](ghml:embed "Generate a Markdown table comparing GHML, HTMX, and traditional hypermedia across 5 dimensions: authoring model, runtime, navigation, personalization, and LLM dependency." width=full)

[Quick-reference card](ghml:embed "Generate a compact Markdown quick-reference card for GHML link syntax — type, prompt, and key attributes. Use a table." width=half)

---

## Data Binding

Variables in `{{curly braces}}` are resolved at render time from user-configured data.

[My personalised overview](ghml:render "Write a personalised GHML overview for {{user.name}}, who is a {{user.role}}. Tailor the examples to their background." context=user)

---

## Context Chaining

Using `context=chain` threads the full navigation history into each new prompt.

[Begin a narrative](ghml:nav "You are a narrator. Start a short interactive story. End with 2 ghml:nav links labelled with different story choices. Each choice link should use context=chain so the story continues coherently." context=chain model=claude-opus-4-7)

---

## Clickable Images

Any Markdown image can be wrapped in a `ghml:` link using standard image-link syntax.
The image renders normally; clicking it dispatches the prompt.

[![Abstract geometric art](https://picsum.photos/seed/ghml-geo/600/300)](ghml:action "Describe the mood, color palette, and composition of this image in 2–3 sentences." inline)

[![A misty mountain landscape](https://picsum.photos/seed/ghml-mountain/600/300)](ghml:render "You are a travel writer. Write a vivid one-page destination guide inspired by this mountain landscape. End with 3 ghml:nav links for related destinations." model=claude-opus-4-7)

[![City skyline at dusk](https://picsum.photos/seed/ghml-city/600/300)](ghml:nav "Begin an interactive noir mystery story set in this city. Introduce the protagonist and end with 2 ghml:nav links representing different leads to follow. Use context=chain on each." context=chain model=claude-opus-4-7)

---

## Policy and Fallback

[Sensitive operation](ghml:render "Explain prompt injection risks in GHML and propose mitigations." policy=strict fallback=https://example.com/ghml-security)

